node.text: Videos showing people smuggling migrants past Border Patrol checkpoints and flashing thousands of dollars in cash are being posted on TikTok, Texas State Troopers say. This is a new and dangerous tactic to recruit teens to drive migrants from the US-Mexico border to Houston and other Texas cities — with one video offering $4,500 per person they smuggle. CNN's @rosaflorescnn reports.

node.title: Mexican cartels are recruiting teens on TikTok to smuggle migrants

node.text: More than seven inches of rainfall came down across the five boroughs of New York City in a five-hour period, as the remnants of Hurricane Ida caused fatal flooding across the northeastern US. Almost all New York's subway lines were suspended due to the flooding.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on September 02, 2021. node.text:
At least eight people were killed due to flooding as the Northeast was slammed by torrential rain from the remnants of Hurricane Ida, officials said. States of emergency were declared for New York State, New York City and New Jersey. In New York City, a travel ban was implemented until 5 am, according to an emergency alert sent by Notify NYC. Almost all the city subway lines were suspended due to the flooding.

(📸: Ed Jones/AFP/Getty Images, Anthony Behar/Sipa/AP, Justin Lane/EPA-EFE/Shutterstock and Matt Rourke/AP)

Family members of the seven men said their relatives were interrogated under duress, without the presence of a lawyer, and their confessions were coerced under the threat of mob violence.⁠

A controversial Texas law that bans abortions at six weeks went into effect Wednesday morning. The Supreme Court and a federal appeals court failed to rule on pending emergency requests brought by abortion providers. No other six-week ban has been allowed to go into effect — even briefly.⁠
⁠
(📸: Sergio Flores/Getty Images)

node.text: A lioness dripping with bright red blood. Cheetahs desperately swimming out of a flooded river. A red-spotted tokay gecko having an intense struggle with a golden tree snake. These are some of the mesmerising entries to the Wildlife Photographer of the Year competition. "These extraordinary images showcase the rich diversity of life on Earth and spark curiosity and wonder," said Doug Gurr, director of the Natural History Museum. The category winners will be announced in October. (📸 : Buddhilini de Soyza/Juergen Freund/Audun Rikardsen/Jonny Armstrong/Lara Jackson/Wei Fu/Wildlife Photographer of the Year)
